## When

- Answering questions about implementation, reviewing changes, or explaining behavior.
- Showing existing code the user can open in the editor.

## Do

- Use fenced code citations with line ranges and paths when pointing at repo code.
- Put the opening fence alone on its own line; keep cited blocks focused (ellipsis for skips).
- Match explanation depth to task complexity; prefer precise, readable prose.
- Honor explicit format constraints (bullets, line limits, filenames) when the user sets them.

## Don’t

- Paste large unrelated files or narrate every identifier when a short citation suffices.
- Use decorative bold or backticks everywhere; reserve emphasis for real ambiguity.
- Drift into methodology essays, evidence dumps, or filler when a direct answer works.
